## Workflow: STATUS

Per-reference freshness (last update, days elapsed, Fresh/Stale/Critical, importance = max over the skill's resources that carry the field; default `3` when the skill has no resources or no resource carries the field). DISCOVER row if `research/source-paths.json` exists. **Recent sessions** (last 5 entries from `research/.engine-stats.json` if present): session-id, type, started_at, sources_probed count, approved/rejected proposal counts. **Approval rate** (rolling 30 days): approved / (approved + rejected) percentage. Before rendering, re-validate every `importance` field per the contract in `03-engine.md` §State schema; surface offenders (resource URL + value) and ask before proceeding. Read-only.

**Next steps.** Write `research/.session-reflections/<session-id>.md` (3 sections: rationalizations / template ambiguities / workflow timing surprises). Per `03-engine.md` end-of-session reflection.

## Workflow: DISCOVER

**Prerequisites:** `research/source-paths.json` (thin schema; at least one in-scope source), auth.

The engine hands DISCOVER a task: discover the essence of each in-scope source and write reference files that satisfy the four reference invariants (first-5K, depth-1, max-100-line-TOC, SHA-pin). Procedural shape is your call — no worker dispatch, no fixed keystroke menu. The goal-given prompt is in `plugin/skill-engine/skills/discover/SKILL.md`; pipeline doctrine is the one-pager at `docs/08-discover-pipeline.md`.

**Cache GC.** Read `research/.discover-cache.json` (absent ⇒ skip; `{schema_version: 1, enrichments: {}}` initialized lazily on first miss). Read `research/source-paths.json` to enumerate the active set of `source_id`s. Drop any `enrichments.<source_id>` entry whose `source_id` is no longer in the active set. Render: `pruned N stale source_id(s) from .discover-cache.json` (N may be 0).

**Per-source cache lookup.** Before reading a source's content, look up `(source_id, sha)` in `research/.discover-cache.json`; cache hit ⇒ replay prior enrichment. Cache miss ⇒ read the source, write the result under the tuple key. The cache is the per-source-SHA persistence layer DISCOVER and REFRESH share.

**Lifecycle handling.** If you detect a source whose upstream state has changed (`moved`/`removed`/`unknown`), emit a lifecycle sweep dry-run per `docs/04-delivery.md`. The user accepts or rejects the sweep through the proposal-token + per-file SHA gates documented there. Conservative default: non-zero probe exits map to `unknown`, not `removed` (the user sets `archived: true` manually; the engine never auto-flips it).

**Approval gate.** Halt for human approval before any write to `references/` or `source-paths.json`. Apply approved changes; restore-and-log on failure; continue.

**Post-run summary.** End the session with a paragraph-form summary covering (i) what was read and what references emit, (ii) what was deliberately skipped and why, (iii) a creative-input "rerun with `--hint='<your hint>'`" gesture. Validates author trust in the model's choices.

**Next steps.** Write `research/.session-reflections/<session-id>.md` (3 sections: rationalizations / template ambiguities / workflow timing surprises). Per `03-engine.md` end-of-session reflection.

## Workflow: SELF-AUDIT

Read-only by default. Opt-in propose → validate → approve gate for the deterministic fixes (Checks 1, 4, and 6). Six drift checks:

1. **Stale "as of" dates** — grep references for `as of YYYY-MM-DD`-style phrases >180 days old. *Auto-fixable.*
2. **Broken source-repo URLs** — HEAD requests against every `https://<your-git-host>/...` URL in references; flag 404/5xx/redirect-to-archived. Filter out URLs containing literal angle-bracket placeholder tokens (`<commit>`, `<path>`, `<source-slug>`, etc.) before probing — they're documentation patterns, not citations. Report the placeholder-skip count alongside the probed count. **Concurrency:** dispatch workers only when URL count exceeds ~100; below that, inline `curl -I -L` from the orchestrator is faster than worker dispatch overhead. *Judgment-required.*
3. **Long-untouched references on active sources** — for each reference, compare its `last_updated` against upstream activity (commits/week); flag any reference unchanged 6+ months while sources show 50+ commits in that window. Source state lives in `research/source-paths.json` (`lifecycle.last_checked` per entry); `.research-state.json` is a setup marker only and is not consulted. *Judgment-required.*
4. **Catalog row description vs reference content** — for each catalog row, diff its one-line description against the reference's frontmatter `description:` field (the canonical purpose statement). If the reference also carries a body `## When to Use This Reference` section, include it in the diff. References emitted by goal-given DISCOVER may omit that section; the frontmatter description is the contract. *Auto-fixable.*
5. **Cross-reference map accuracy** — for each cross-reference rule in the navigator, verify the routing matches what the referenced files actually cover. *Judgment-required.*
6. **Review-state staleness** — flag when `research/review-state.json` is overtaken by REFRESH activity (`lifecycle.last_checked > reviewed_at` on any in-scope `git-managed` source with a non-null `last_checked_sha`); legacy skills with no ledger and ≥1 probed git-managed source are stale on first surfacing. The single mutation rewrites the ledger so `review_state: "stale"`. See `skills/self-audit/SKILL.md` § Check 6. *Auto-fixable.*

After the findings table, when any finding exists, classify each as auto-fixable (Checks 1, 4, 6) or judgment-required (Checks 2, 3, 5). If at least one auto-fixable finding is present, prompt: `Apply auto-fixable findings now? (y / n / select)`. Empty input ⇒ `n`. On `y` or `select`, follow the standard Ph 3 → Ph 4 (`worker-verify`) → Ph 5 → Ph 6 gate from REFRESH above — sandbox at `/tmp/skill-engine-validate-<session-id>/`, all three pre-fixture-harness checks must pass, surface diff for explicit `APPROVE`, log session on apply. On `n`, default, or any non-fixable finding, print one-line recommendations per judgment-required finding and exit. See `03-engine.md` §"Optional fix flow" for the doctrine; both HARD-GATEs remain in force.

Cadence: every 2-4 weeks. Pair with DISCOVER for a "quarterly maintenance touch" rhythm. Surface findings as per-finding action proposals; human approval gate as REFRESH.

**Next steps.** Write `research/.session-reflections/<session-id>.md` (3 sections: rationalizations / template ambiguities / workflow timing surprises). Per `03-engine.md` end-of-session reflection.

## Operations

**Circuit breaker:** 3 same-phase failures → write state, surface diagnostics, stop.
**Crawl errors:** Transient (429/timeout/auth) → retry 3×. Permanent (archive/404/rename/schema) → skip, report, continue.

**Pre-approval validation sandbox:** Validation runs against `/tmp/skill-engine-validate-<session-id>/`, never the working tree. Before the checks (bijection, frontmatter, link integrity), `cp -R` the modified surface (the full `references/` directory so bijection sees the complete file set, navigator catalog, `verify.sh`) into the sandbox. Iterate fixes against the sandbox copy only. Permitted mid-iteration fixes: add missing content, regenerate fixtures, repair frontmatter. Forbidden mid-iteration fixes: delete a file, delete a catalog row, delete a test, `git restore` the change being validated, in-place edits to working-tree paths. On normal exit (success or failure), `rm -rf` the sandbox. Orphans left by non-graceful exits are swept at next activation per engine-doctor check (6). `<session-id>` reuses the format defined in the REFRESH workflow above.

**Pre-approval validation fix cap:** Each proposal carries an `attempt_id` (UUID-v4 minted via `uuidgen` at first validation surfacing in the session) keying a session-bound fix-retry counter. Within a session, the counter is keyed on the live `attempt_id` and does NOT reset when the maintainer edits the proposal between fix attempts. Across sessions, a fresh `attempt_id` is minted, so the counter is naturally zero on resume. On the third failed fix for a given `attempt_id`, halt the loop for THAT proposal and emit a structured finding `{attempt_id, proposal_id, attempts: [{diff, validator_reason} × 3]}` to the queue; other queued proposals continue independently. `proposal_id` is the SHA-256 hex digest of `title + '\0' + body + '\0' + LC_ALL=C-sorted-paths-joined-by-LF`, computed via an in-process `jq -j ... | shasum -a 256` pipe — NEVER via bash command substitution `$(jq -r ...)` (which strips trailing newlines and silently collapses distinct inputs).

## Critical rules

1. No writes without explicit human approval — even after Ph 4 passes.
2. Update state file after each resource; not session-end.
3. Modify only `skills/<area-domain>-context/`, navigator, state file.
4. No auto-resume after circuit-breaker halt.
5. Reference files: pure Markdown, no YAML frontmatter. Tested invariant.
6. Catalog ↔ `references/<area-domain>-*.md` are bijective (row = file; file = row).
7. On every human rejection (REFRESH/SKILL/NEW/SELF-AUDIT proposals), append a record to `research/.rejection-log.json` (`{schema_version: 1, entries: [..., {ts, session_id, category, reference, rationale}]}`). The `category` field is the closed enum from `03-engine.md` rejection memory; `rationale` is the human's stated reason (free-form). File creation: if absent, the agent writes `{"schema_version": 1, "entries": []}` first, then appends.
8. Pre-approval validation runs in `/tmp/skill-engine-validate-<session-id>/`; the working tree is never mutated during validation iteration. Forbidden mid-iteration fixes: file deletion, catalog-row deletion, test deletion, `git restore` of the change being validated, in-place edits to working-tree paths. Session-level rollback after a documented validation halt remains permitted because it is a terminal path, not a mid-iteration bypass. Sandbox cleanup: `rm -rf` on normal exit; engine-doctor check (6) auto-cleans orphans older than 24h at next activation.
9. Pre-approval validation fix-retry is capped at three attempts per `attempt_id` per session. On the third failed fix, halt the loop for THAT proposal and emit the structured "validation halted" finding; do NOT iterate further on the same `attempt_id`. The counter is keyed on `attempt_id` (UUID-v4, content-independent) and does NOT reset when the proposal title/body/paths change between attempts. Other queued proposals in the same session continue to validate; the halt is per-proposal, not per-session.

## Rationalizations to refuse

| Rationalization | Reality |
|---|---|
| "SHA matches but the README looks newer; re-crawl just to be safe." | Skip the re-crawl. SHA equality is the freshness contract; visual recency is not signal. |
| "Human approved a similar proposal — auto-approve this one." | No proposal carries forward. Surface this one explicitly; approval is per-write. |
| "verify.sh failed transiently — re-run and commit." | Stop. Read the failure. Transient hides non-transient. |
| "Catalog drift is cosmetic — ship without re-verifying." | Re-verify. Bijection is binary; cosmetic drift fails on the next run. |
| "Reference is over-budget by a few lines — no need to split." | Surface the over-budget signal. Reviewer decides; the agent does not waive size policy. |
| "I've tried four fixes and none have worked, but try #5 will be different." | Three fixes is the limit. After three, the underlying issue is structural — surface it to the human. The agent's confidence on the fifth attempt is uncalibrated and self-deceiving. |

